// @check
// @error argument 1: expected (i32, i32) -> i32, got (any, any) -> string
// A generic (un-annotated-param) function is sound to use as a VALUE only when it is monomorphized
// per use — a direct-call-only `const g = add` alias (value-flow-mono.vl). Where it ESCAPES into a
// position expecting a CONCRETE function type, its type `(any, any) -> …` does not satisfy the
// concrete `(i32, i32) -> i32`, so the checker rejects it here — it can never be `call_ref`'d
// soundly at that type. (Passing it to an UN-annotated higher-order param, which the checker can't
// pin, is caught one tier later by the emit-time value floor — `cannot take a generic function …
// as a value`.) This guards that relaxing the floor for direct-call aliases did NOT let a generic
// function value slip into a concrete function-typed slot.
function add(a, b) a + b
function apply2(f: (i32, i32) => i32) f(10, 20)

print(apply2(add)) // REJECTED: a generic function value can't satisfy (i32, i32) -> i32
